ce:section.ce:para:
In our study, ammonia solution was chosen as N source to prepare high luminescent NCDs. NCD samples prepared at 120, 140, 160, 180, 200 and 220°C are used to study the effect of reaction temperature on the structure and fluorescence properities of NCDs. NCDs-120 was not characterized because of the very weak fluorescence of its aqueous solution and high stickiness of its solid. The effect of nitrogen on structures and fluorescence properties of CDs is also investigated by comparison of NCDs-180 and N-free CDs-180. The HRTEM images in Fig. 1
                         show all NCD samples and N-free CDs-180 possess a nearly spherical shape. The statistical particle size distributions of the NCDs-140 (Fig. 1a), NCDs-160 (Fig. 1b), NCDs-180 (Fig. 1c), NCDs-200 (Fig. 1d), NCDs-220 (Fig. 1e) and N-free CDs-180 (Fig. 1f) are 2.5–6nm, 2–10nm, 1.5–4.5nm, 2–5nm, 3–7nm and 1.5–4.5nm, with average diameters of 4.25±0.25nm, 5±0.5nm, 2.75±0.25nm, 3.25±0.25nm, 4.75±0.25nm and 2.75±0.25nm, respectively, indicating that they all have a relatively narrow size distribution. The overall size of NCDs shows a fluctuation of increase (140–160°C), decrease (160–180°C) and increase (180–220°C) as the reaction temperature increases. Compared with NCDs-180 (Fig. 1c), N-free CDs-180 (Fig. 1f) shows no noticeable change in size, indicating that doping N does not increase the particle sizes. In addition, NCDs-140 shows apperant aggeration. When the temperature increases to 160°C, aggeration is alleviated to some extent, while when the temperature is equal or higher than 180°C, NCDs (Fig. 1c–e) are well dispersed without apparent aggregation. Similar with NCDs-180, N-free CDs-180 is also well dispersed without apparent aggregation, indicating that doping N does not influence dispersion of CDs. Moreover, HRTEM images show that all NCDs and N-free CDs-180 (Fig. 1a–f) do not reveal any obvious lattice fringes, indicating their amorphous nature, as also reported by other researchers [3,9–11]. Typical XRD patterns (Fig. 2
                        ) of all NCDs and N-free CDs-180 further show broader and weak (002) diffraction peaks centered at about 2θ=28.0° (3.4Å), which are assigned to highly disordered carbon structures [3,8–10,12]. XRD result indicates that doping N does not influence disordered carbon structures of CDs. All the HRTEM and XRD results are well consistent, supporting that NCDs and N-free CDs-180 are amorphous nanoparticles without discernible lattice structures.

To further explore the optical properties of the NCDs synthesized at temperature of 120, 140, 160, 180, 200 and 220°C, PL and UV–vis absorption properties were investigated (Fig. 5
                        a–c). For the UV–vis absorption spectra of NCDs (Fig. 5a and b), NCDs-120 has no obvious peak at 235 and 335nm; whereas for NCDs prepared from 140 to 220°C, a new typical absorption band blue-shifts from 338 to 328nm, while absorption intensity increases in 140–180°C range and then decreases in 180–220°C. In addition, the intensity of absorption band at 235nm shows similar change rules as that at about 335nm. The two absorption bands centered at 235nm and 335nm are related to π–π* transitions of the aromatic CC and n-π* transition of CO or COH bond of NCDs, respectively [2]. This result reveals that reaction temperature can affect the absorption properties of as-synthesized NCDs [9]. For N-free CDs-180, there is only a broad UV–vis absorption below 270nm (Fig. 5d), indicating doping nitrogen can change absorption properties of CDs. As shown in the fluorescence spectra of NCDs (Fig. 5c), upon excitation at 360nm, PL intensity at 440nm also shows similar changes as UV–vis absorbance with increasing reaction temperature. However, PL peak keeps unchanged at 440nm for NCDs prepared in the range of 120–180°C, while it slightly blue-shifts to 435nm for NCDs-200 and NCDs-220 (Fig. 5c). This result reveals that the increase of reaction temperature can also lead to the blueshift of the maximum emission wavelengths. Interestingly, at different temperatures, although we obtain transparent black-blue (140–160°C), green (180°C) and light-brown (200–220°C) dispersions, they all exhibit a bright blue fluorescence under illumination of 365nm UV lamp as shown in Table 1, which corresponds to their PL spectra (Fig. 6
                        ). Moreover, we also obtain black-blue (140–160°C) stick asphalt solid, black-green (180°C) and brown-yellow (200–220°C) powder. None of them exhibits bright blue fluorescence because of apperant floorescence quenching under illumination of 365nm UV lamp as shown in Table 1. Being auxochromes, amino-groups should enhance the optical absorption of NCDs, resulting in a deeper color of dispersion. Consequently, the NCDs prepared at lower temperatures (140–160°C) exhibit blue-black/blue-green color, which confirms a higher density of amino-groups on their surface [5]. Compared with the PL spectra (Fig. 6d) and Photoes (Table 1) of NCDs-180, the PL spectra of the N-free CDs-180 show the optimal emission peak at 440nm upon excitation at 360nm. From the photographs shown in Table 1, the aqueous solution of N-free CDs-180 is colourless and transparent in daylight but displays very weak blue fluorescence when the sample is irradiated by 365nm UV light, which corresponds to their PL spectra (Figs. 5 d and 6 g). It is noteworthy that although O is a strong electron acceptor, the N-free CDs-180 also shows weak luminescence. This is due to lots of oxygen-containing groups (such as COOH and OH), always inducing non-radiative recombination of localized electron–hole pairs and holding back the intrinsic state emission [32]. From the photographs shown in Table 1, the N-free CDs-180 powder is white in daylight but displays white color when the sample is irradiated by 365nm UV light.
